04476nam a22005775i 9780774850049DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072001xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748500497 a10.59962/97807748500492doi  a(DE-B1597)661702  a(OCoLC)741451959  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aKE332.W6bB764 2001eb 7aLAW0430002bisacsh04a331.4/133/09711 aBrockman, Joan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGender in the Legal Profession :bFitting or Breaking the Mould /cJoan Brockman. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw and Society00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tLaw’s Attractions and Detractions -- tFitting In -- tDiscrimination and Sexual Harassment -- tReluctant Adversaries -- tThe Balancing Act: Careers, Co-Habitors, Children, and Chores -- tBreaking the Mould -- tAppendix: Income Analysis -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe history of the legal profession in Canada and elsewhere is one of the exclusion of women, Aboriginals, ethnic and racial minorities, and those from less privileged classes. Based on face-to-face interviews with 50 women and 50 men called to the Bar in British Columbia during the past 3-7 years, Joan Brockman has studied this phenomenon and tried to determine reasons why such exclusion has been practised and what its effects have been, particularly with respect to women. Although legal barriers that historically prevented women from entering the legal profession have been removed, informal and structural barriers that impede women's full participation within the profession remain. Much of the discrimination still experienced stems from expectations that women, in particular, will assume primary responsibilities for child care, elder care, emotional stability in the home, household management, and other domestic matters. In addition, some women still experience sexual harassment and discrimination even if they have managed to reduce or avoid additional domestic responsibilities. There have, to be sure, been changes and accommodations made for women in the legal workforce, and men as well as women have helped to make them. But, Brockman concludes, until there is significant change in how women are perceived in relation to domestic duties, it is unlikely that they will attain equality within the legal profession. The profession will only change when perceptions of the family change, at which point women will not only fit the mould at work, but men also will fit the mould at home.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSex discrimination against womenzCanada. 0aSex discrimination in employmentzCanada. 0aWomen lawyerszCanada. 7aLAW / Gender & the Law.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485004940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774850049423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774850049/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles